	   <tr><td colspan=2>Welcome to the brotherhood of Druids! I think you'll find the class richly rewarding and fun to play.<br><br>I, too, chose a halfling druid, due to Misty Thicket (widely felt to be the best newbie zone in the game), less competition for spawns in my newbie zone (MT versus GFay), several really good starting quests (Hungry Deputy, Carrots for Karana, etc.),&nbsp;&nbsp;the halfling (supposedly) levels faster due to a smaller racial xp penalty,  and I felt thebeginning stats of a halfling were (for my style of play) superior to wood elves.<br><br>Your halfling has superior STR, STA and DEX to a wood elf, while having inferior INT and CHA. If you plan to use the Charm Animals line of spells down the road, you'll want to consider playing a wood elf druid because length of charm is at least partially tied to your character's charisma. Also, if you plan to do tradecraft, the wood elf's starting INT being higher will aid that pursuit. As nearly as I can tell, that about exhausts the advantages of playing a wood elf over the halfling.<br><br>I think I put all my starting points (30) into WIS. Upon reflection, I might have put a few points into CHA to help with prices from and to merchants.  That's totally up to you what what concept under which you want to play your druid. However you decide to proceed, as I said above, I think you'll have a real blast with the treehugger. I know I have.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
