	   <tr><td colspan=2>First off, you should always train once in all areas of specialization.&nbsp;&nbsp;Only one will go over 49, but every little bit helps in the others as well.  I heard that at one time, you had to train in them all for one to improve, but don't know if that bug still exists.<br><br>I favor evocation as the over-50 specialization for druids.  Your DD's and flame-line DOT's are evocations, and you'll usually be casting DD's when really eating through your mana.  When fighting in groups, this is the one you need.<br><br>If your favorite group doesn't include a cleric and you find yourself healing a lot during battle, alteration would be a good second choice.<br><br>If you're grouping, you're likely only casting one conjuration spell per mob, so it's not worth having that as your prime specialization.  If you primarily solo and like to DOT and run, you might consider conjuration, as the swarm line are the highest-damage DOT's, and the flame-line ones that also lower AC aren't going to benefit you as much since you plan to avoid closing with the creature.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
